20. What are Continuous and Categorical Variables?
Answer20- In Machine Learning and Statistics, variables are the characteristics or attributes of data that 
can have different values. These variables are generally classified into two main types: continuous 
variables and categorical variables.
Continuous Variables
Continuous variables are numerical variables that can take any value within a specific range. These 
values are measurable and can include decimal points or fractions. There is no fixed limit on the 
number of values they can have.
Examples:
• Height of a person 
• Weight of a student 
• Temperature of a city 
• Salary of an employee 
• Distance traveled by a vehicle 
For example, a person's height can be 165 cm, 165.5 cm, or 165.75 cm. Therefore, height is a 
continuous variable.
Categorical Variables
Categorical variables represent different groups, categories, or labels. Instead of numerical 
measurements, they describe the qualities or classifications of data.
Examples:
• Gender (Male, Female) 
• Blood Group (A, B, AB, O) 
• City Names 
• Marital Status 
• Department Names 
For example, a student's blood group can be A, B, AB, or O. These values represent categories rather 
than measurable quantities.
Thus, continuous variables represent measurable quantities, whereas categorical variables represent 
different groups or classes.
21. What is Feature Scaling? How does it help in Machine Learning?
Answer21- Feature Scaling is the process of transforming numerical data so that all features have a 
similar range of values. In many datasets, some features may have very large values while others have 
very small values. This difference can affect the performance of machine learning algorithms.
For example, consider a dataset containing:
• Age: 18 to 60 
• Salary: 20,000 to 1,00,000 
Here, salary values are much larger than age values. As a result, the model may give more importance 
to salary and ignore age. Feature scaling helps solve this problem.
Benefits of Feature Scaling
1. Improves the performance of machine learning algorithms. 
2. Speeds up the training process. 
3. Helps the model converge faster. 
4. Prevents features with large values from dominating the learning process. 
5. Improves prediction accuracy in many algorithms. 
Feature scaling is especially important in algorithms such as K-Nearest Neighbors (KNN), Support 
Vector Machines (SVM), Logistic Regression, and Neural Networks.
Therefore, feature scaling helps create a balanced dataset and improves the efficiency of machine 
learning models.
22. How do we perform Scaling in Python?
Answer22- Scaling in Python is commonly performed using the Scikit-Learn library. The library 
provides several preprocessing techniques that help transform numerical features into a similar range.
One of the most commonly used methods is StandardScaler.
